caption: Delicious Jewish Japanese fusion restaurant! Have come here twice for brunch and it has always been fantastic. We got the okonomiyaki and the Wagyu pastrami sando and they were so good! The plates are also beautiful, the chef himself makes them and they’re available for purchase on their website. Very good service and they have a nice outdoor seating area. Can’t wait to come back to try the dinner menu.
This is a true Williamsburg gem! The staff is extremely friendly and the food is very tasty. I would highly recommend the teriyaki duck wings!!

THIS PLACE IS NOT KOSHER! Although they advertise to Hebrews in Brooklyn, this place is NOT kosher. They have a strict mask policy... basically if youre not eating or drinking, mask ON. Mask on between bites and courses!!

Smaller than expected portions. Delicious food.  I docked two stars because outdoor seating is currently a mess and I nearly froze, even though the heater was on. There are openings on all sides and the heater is not doing anything. Also, they plug in the heater after someone is sitting down, which means it takes a while before it even turns on.
Horrible service they make you wear a mask till the food comes wasn’t even good... yet they seat people so close to each other ... way better restaurants around the area save your time and money
Never ate there, but charged 100. Who knows, maybe it was good.

Great service (Rose was excellent), very COVID friendly (indoor dining and outdoor), the food was expensive but DELICIOUS. The matzo ball ramen in particular was incredible and the miso roasted oysters were a great treat.
Food is delicious. Definitely 5 stars. Great customer service. Highly recommend this place

I had high hopes but what a disappointment. Sad. Where to begin? The food had nothing Japanese, nada. After a $ 350 Valentine’s prefix, I’m still hungry and in pursue of some sushi, teriyaki, soba, udon or ramen. Even the dessert selection had nothing Japanese, it was a bad experience. To top it all, the customer service from the guy host was awful, perhaps the worst in all of NYC. The lady and server were fine. Perhaps their day-to-day meals are better, but the prefix course was poor.

We went here for the Valentine’s Day special and it was disappointing. The portions were pretty small and lacked the Japanese flare. The main course was more like Korean hot pot instead of ramen which was confusing too.
Great food and service the staff was super accommodating setting up a table for us over to the side when the tents where full. Matzoh ball ramen was delicious.
Always great food, good service and some fun dishes you can't find anywhere else.
Portions weren’t great! I was excited about the sweet potato cheesecake that I tasted in Japan but didn’t taste like it. Wagyu beef sandwich and challah bread side was awesome. Noodle was just okay.
I eat in this spot a lot since I work close by. I like how the service is always great and they keep the spot well organized at all times. Rates are convenient and they serve big portions.
So original! A pure mix of culture. For the first time Japanese flavors meets Jewish deli.  It’s good, fresh, original. Nothing fancy here just a great experience.

4.5 stars. The food was really good: ramen, seafood, dessert. Okonomiyaki was not memorable. Service was great. We were here during winter of the pandemic. Heaters were not that effective because it gets slightly windy, you’ll need a good jacket if seated outside.

The food is well thought out and creative but SUPER pricy with only average execution.  Ordered a potato latke for $22 and it was fairly small, and a tiny bowl of blanched broccoli for $11. The broccoli was a bit too soft.  Walked out starving with a huge bill, but enjoyed the experience nevertheless. Great service.
Loved the Matzoh Ball Ramen. And their staff is really welcoming.

Good but not great. Had the Matzoh Ball Ramon.  Tasted very good. Excellent matzoh ball. But the noodles were all stuck together so they were obviously stored and just dropped in the soup prior to serving. Took a while to have to aerate them.  Also there was only one piece of very fatty chicken thrown in.  Ordered the extra egg which was cooked to perfection. Also had the Pastrami Sando. Which is just pastrami on Japanese white bread and mustard.  But for $19, there was maybe 4 ounces of meat on the sandwich which doesn’t really compare with a traditional sandwich.  The pastrami was excellent though.  I asked if they would sell me the meat by the pound and they would - $56 a pound.  Wow. Nice place. Worth trying once.
Cute, but pricey for the portion.

The food are amazing and well thought out. A great example of fusion as each dish was meticulously prepared with great flavor and presentation. The waiter was friendly and helpful. You have to give this place a try.

We also did the sake tasting, which was super fun as the sake guru  came by and explained to us some fun facts/history of each sake we were drinking! Really awesome and creative Japanese fusion dishes. The pastrami wagyu sando was an absolute standout and really representative of the Jewish Japanese crossover. The service is great and the drinks were wonderful. Great place for socially distant outdoor dining during COVID.

The Tuna Tataki has a black tahini sauce that is really special! My friends had the Matzoh Ball Ramen as a main and said it was amazing as well. The service was wonderful and super friendly. There’s also a cocktail and sake menu. Looking forward to going back soon!

This restaurant is highly unreliable and has awful service. My boyfriend made us a reservation for Valentine’s Day one week in advance for 6:45pm. When we both finished our busy days, we were on our way when the restaurant calls and decided to cancel our reservation and give the slot to another couple (they probably overbooked themselves and kicked us off for no reason). They claimed they had called us several times throughout the week and left a voicemail to confirm the reservation but we had no calls so it clearly made up. Both the owner and the manager treated us like trash even though they ruined our vday day. It was too late to get a reservation anywhere else so our night was ruined. They didn’t offer to accommodate us at the bar or anything to remedy the situation. They also have our credit card information and said they might charge a cancellation fee. DO NOT COME HERE FOR SPECIAL OCCASIONS, they are not reliable and have horrible service and policies.

My wife and I really wanted to like it here, she is Jewish (nice that they mix in some Jewish staples on the menu), we both love Japanese food, and it's nearby home for us. But unfortunately, the experience continued to degrade throughout the night.  First, we were told that in order to do omakase, we both had to do so. I wanted my meal to be duck-heavy with one or two apps for additional flavor,so doing the $75 chef's selection didn't make much sense. I can understand how some restaurants would require this to truly bring out the experience of omakase, but given this was simply a tasting menu and we observed the lone diner next to us cycle through the tasting samples, it didn't seem wise that the man in the kitchen (whom appeared to be the manager) would put the kibosh on this. The same man whom my wife later witnessed put his fingers in her rice to taste for himself.  On top of all that, we incidentally learned that the glass of hot sake is a better value than the carafe. Initially we ordered a carafe, but they only brought a glass. Once we ordered the carafe, we were very skeptical that it was much more volume than the glass, so we did a trial by ordering another glass and measured out that the carafe was hardly more than the glass (1.5x at best estimate), while being double the price.  We will say that the food was great, but the restaurant just seemed like a poorly ran operation, so we will struggle to convince ourselves to go back.

Great service, food was delicious and presentation was delightful as well. Came here for a special occasion and ordered the tasting menu which was delicious. Will definitely be back to try even more of the menu. Drinks and sake we're impressive as well.

So yeah, the food is interesting.  Not great, just...interesting. The "Jew Egg" (think "ramen egg inside a falafel") is a great idea, undermined by undersalting (and $15!) The okonomiyaki with pastrami is *excellent*, but $15 for a wee tiny one. The "lox bowl" (think "chirashi w/ lox-like stuff") has excellent rice, but *seriously* sub-par uni (and is $25)  And the list goes on. Everything is ok to good, but around 40% more pricey than it should be  In short, interesting, but not worth a second visit (or a first one, quite frankly)  (Oh, excellent sake list, fwiw)

Delicious food and friendly service. We got the okonomiyaki and matzo ball ramen and they were both excellent. Server offered to give us extra bowls and plates to share. Low noise levels and simple yet unique decor
Great selection of an unusual fusion of Jewish and Japanese food. Waiting staff were very attentive and helpful.
Amazing food.
Hate this place! Terrible service, terrible location.
It's expensive, but this is one of the few times a fusion restaurant is worth it.  The matzo ball ramen, latke, and Jew egg are crazy delicious and as good as you'd want them to be.
I love Japan
This place wants to bring the flavors of Jewish food, but they're not kosher!! And the bread doesn't look or taste like challah bread.
Good in theory, misses the mark a bit.  Priced too high, IMHO.  Still 4 stars for the concept and for trying

I've been here so many times it ridiculous. The food speaks for itself on the love the two chefs have for it and every dish is well executed but also fun. Have the okonomiyaki, Challah, and the Matzo Ball ramen and you'll understand.

The five star is for the jew egg, and their version of pancake...  The jew egg for being unique and different, taste wise maybe not what I expected, but still not bad.  Their Japanese pancake  "Okonomiyaki" was so inventive, and so full of flavors, it was hitting all the right spots...    From the Bonita fish flakes on top to the pastrami...  I would go back just for that.  Honorable mentions: Matzoh Ball Ramen with Foie Gras Dumpling, and the seared tuna.

(Translated by Google) Delicious food, friendly service. Especially the interpretation of the Jewish Egg you have to try.  (Original) Sehr leckeres Essen, freundlicher Service. Besonders die Interpretation des Jewish Egg muss man probieren.
Do not miss the tuna tataki
Japanese. Jewish. Fun and lively ambiance. Flavourful menu.
Good food
Awesome restaurant! Food was delicious, great and fresh concept! Service was good and they were very welcoming!
Very innovative menu and most of the food was delicious. Food was 5 stars, especially the duck wings and tuna. Was a bit on the pricey side given location, hence the 4 star review

Rarely is fusion done right, but this place is spot on. Gorged myself at dinner, on the Okonomiyaki (latke) + a decadent ramen + wings. (I had help!) Not crowded, friendly, quick service. Definitely going back.
Highly recommend New Year’s Duck, Scallops, Grilled Chrysanthemum Greens & Kale. You're fine skipping the Lox Bowl. By far the best feature of this place is the Hitachino Nest White Ale on tap

I wanted to eat Shalom Japan ever since I heard the name. Hilarious! It has a really nice atmosphere and gracious service. My favorite dishes were the teriyaki duck wings; the scallop sashimi with turnip, Asian pears and shiso; okonomiyaki with pastrami and bonito flakes. We really enjoyed the matzo ball ramen . The texture of the matzo ball was perfect. The Jew egg was nicely executed in terms of technique, but the falafel coating needed more seasoning. The tongue salad lacked the pizzazz of the other dishes.

Ah-mazing. Each dish was a masterpiece in true fusion. Standout dishes were the okonomiyaki with pastrami, the duck wings, the steak tartare. You don't need the omakaze as a La carte portions are very generous. Truly a gem... Thank you Google maps for the rec!
hands down one of the best places I've been in Brooklyn lately. great atmosphere and amazing food! the cocktails are delicious and the small plates are creative and perfect for sharing.
We had the 5 course omakase and everything was delicious. The beef short rib cholent and lox bowl were highlights.
(Translated by Google) It was delicious! ! !  (Original) すごくおいしかったです！！！
Its a really fun idea with a pretty tasty menu. Start with the Challach soaked in Sake. The butter spread is perfect combination.
Amazing, amazing, amazing! I would eat here every day if I could. Recently went for brunch, and had amazing food and perfect service. New favorite restaurant in Williamsburg!
Delicious! Not cheap but fantastic food.
Shalom was amazing! Gem in the neighborhood. Definitely worth trying out.
Great vibes. Real good service.  Creative drinks. Try the challah bread, the chicken, or the lamb ribs. Yummy!!
I expected the food to be good, but this was world-class. Each dish we got was delicious, and the cuisine was truly unique. The food was comforting and exotic at the same time. Reasonably priced too.

Exceptional dining experience.  Aaron Israel and Sawa Okochi have created a truly special restaurant, with a thoughtful, inventive and delicious menu executed to perfection. The drinks are stellar, the space is cozy and the service is excellent. Shalom Japan leaves you smiling and satiated all night.
